Digital Transformation of Decision-Making in Finance
    V0.2 – title updated, simplified. shifts thesis from “finance only” → into managerial innovation

The Question
    “How can portfolio manager react to sudden information shocks without falling into cognitive traps?”

Pitch
    Managers across industries face unexpected information shocks -- news, announcements, regulatory updates, or public statements -- that often trigger fast decisions under pressure. These reactions are frequently shaped by behavioral biases such as overreaction, anchoring, or availability. My thesis aims to design and test a decision-support system that helps managers evaluate such shocks in a more structured, bias-aware, and evidence-based way.

What the Thesis Will Do (we narrow down object to financial portfolio only)
    1.	Construct financial portfolio to use that as object for experiments. 
    2.	Collect primary data by gathering and classifying:
    •	a large set of external events about holdings in the portfolio	
    •	portfolio managers’ reactions to those events
    3.	Develop a Shock Impact Score that quantifies shock severity and relevance.
    4.	Test the system empirically, using a financial portfolio to compare short-term performance with and without Score-based decision assistance.
    5.	Demonstrate how the system mitigates behavioral overreaction
    6.	Generalize the framework so that it applies not only to finance but to any managerial context

Framework
    External Shocks -> Text Processing -> Severity and Sentiment -> Shock Score -> Descision Correction -> Short Term Performance Indicators

 
Why It Matters
    This approach combines behavioral economics, decision science, and AI into a practical tool that supports better managerial judgement. It helps to process unexpected events and control behavioral biases.
    Potential Value Added (Academic and Practical Contribution)
    Managerial Value
