    •	Helps reduce behavioral overreaction, anchoring, availability bias, and emotional responses.
    •	Supports decision processes in environments under high uncertainty.
    •	Enables organizations to distinguish between “noise” events and events requiring strategic action.
    Methodological Value
    •	Introduces a novel Shock Impact Score (SIS) that quantifies the severity and relevance of external information shocks.
    •	Demonstrates how AI-based text processing improves information filtering and signal identification.
    •	Shows how primary data in the form of news events can be systematically structured for empirical analysis.
    Strategic Value for Firms
    •	Helps senior leaders, risk managers, and analysts evaluate whether to adjust plans, resources, or portfolios.
    •	Enhances operational risk management through better information processing.
    •	Contributes to digital transformation in managerial decision-support systems.
    Academic Value
    Bridges behavioral economics, decision science, AI applications, and risk management.
    Offers a scalable model that can be extended to other domains (supply chain, marketing, operations).

High-Level Approach / Research Plan
    Phase 1 – Conceptual Foundation
    •	Review literature on behavioral biases, managerial overreaction, decision-support systems, AI in decision processes, and announcement effects.
    •	Define constructs: external information shock, decision response, performance indicator, overreaction, etc.
    Phase 2 – Primary Data Collection
    •	Collect and classify a large set of external information shocks (news, announcements, filings, public statements).
    •	Use AI tools to extract sentiment, severity, and categories of shocks.
    •	Label shocks with metadata (timing, type, source credibility).
    Phase 3 – Development of the Shock Impact Score
    •	Combine variables such as sentiment, shock type, similarity to historical events, and market reaction patterns.
    •	Create the SIS as a composite indicator.
    Phase 4 – Empirical Evaluation with a Portfolio Testbed
    •	Apply SIS to a financial portfolio as an experimental environment.
    •	Measure short-term abnormal returns, volatility changes, and deviations from expected behavior.
    •	Compare performance under:
    •	No decision support
    •	SIS-assisted decisions
    •	Simple rule-based hedging or adjustment
    Phase 5 – Managerial Decision Analysis
    •	Evaluate how SIS could help prevent behavioral overreaction.
    •	Optionally collect expert opinions or a small survey validating perceived usefulness.
    •	Phase 6 – Conclusions and Recommendations
    •	Summarize insights for managerial practice.
    •	Discuss ethical and SDG implications (AI transparency, responsible decision-making).
    •	Provide a framework for integrating SIS into broader management processes.

Backtesting
    To see how the system actually works in practice, I will run two kinds of backtests. 
    First, I’ll use a real financial portfolio to compare decisions made normally versus decisions made with the Shock Impact Score guiding reactions to unexpected news. This will show whether the system helps avoid overreactions and improves short-term outcomes. 
    Second, I’ll create a hypothetical company—based on Vostok Finance Group—to model how a real organization might behave when external shocks hit. By simulating its decisions with and without the system, I can demonstrate how the framework could support managers, stabilize reactions, and make the company more resilient overall. This two-step approach keeps the idea practical and easy to understand.
    Is the research new?
    The combination of elements we are proposing is new because it integrates four domains that are rarely combined:
    •	AI-assisted text processing of external information shocks
    •	A composite scoring system designed to guide managerial behavior
    •	An explicit focus on reducing behavioral biases (overreaction, anchoring, availability)
    •	A dual backtesting approach: portfolio + hypothetical company
    •	Most existing research isolates one of these dimensions, but not the full system.
    Academically, this qualifies as original applied methodology, which is exactly what an EMBA thesis requires.

